metadata.name: In Due Time #139
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Interactive Seeds #16
metadata.description:
This interactive piece brings back some good old childhood memory.

Click anywhere on the canvas to blow the seeds away.
The closer to the seeds you click, the stronger the wind force applied to them.

Want to play again?
Just press 'r' to pull the seeds back.

Have fun!

Made with p5.js.


[ Controls - live mode only]

Mouse
- press: blow seeds away from the cursor
- release: stop blowing and freeze the frame

Keys
- r: rewind to pull back the seeds
- 1: minimal resolution 1000x1000 (Default)
- 2: medium resolution 2000x2000
- 4: high resolution 4000x4000
- s: save the image as PNG


[ Special Thanks ]

- Daniel Shiffman for the free eBook "The Nature of Code"
- Warped Perception for the YouTube video "Dandelions Blown - In 4K Slow Motion"


[ Features ]
1. Aspect Ratio: 1x1 / 2x3 / 3x2 / 3x4 / 4x3
2. Dandelions: 1 / 2 / 3 / 4
3. Palette: Sky and Hills / Grayscale / I'm feeling lucky / Just the Dandelions
4. Frame: None / Random / Rounded
5. Background: Single Color / Solid Shapes
6. Seed: Y / I

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #269
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #19
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Mines #129
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: Electric Hope #343
metadata.description:

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Inspired by CMYK halftone printing patterns

Made with p5js especially for #fxhashturnsone event. 50% of primary sales will be donated to Processing Foundation

metadata.name: A Less Traveled Path #109
metadata.description:
"I shall be telling this with a sigh
Somewhere ages and ages hence:
Two roads diverged in a wood, and I—
I took the one less traveled by,
And that has made all the difference."

- Robert Frost, The Road Not Taken



=========

Controls:
[1] set resolution to 1024x1024 (default)
[2] set resolution to 2048x2048 
[3] set resolution to 4096x4096
[0] set resolution to window size (might help on lower end computers)

[c] capture a screenshot at rendered resolution


Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment
XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Prophecy #219
metadata.description:
Elder Futhark Runes / Proto-Germanic alphabets flowing through the canvas.

Each iteration gets a random rune from 24 runes and the vector field angles are based on that.

Also picks one word from what the random rune symbolizes as a prophecy for the next year.

Minted for #fxhashturnsone event 18.11.2022.

50% of primary profits to Processing Foundation.

Save image with 's'.

Load 2x or 4x dimensions (2560 * 3840px) image with '2' or '4'.
